Hi Korey,

Project Summary:
=95 Problem: Random Forests default to 100 trees, but determining the true =
optimal count requires either expensive grid search (accurate but slow) or =
approximate methods like Bayesian optimization (fast but imprecise)
=95 Proposed Solution: Two-Phase Search algorithm that theoretically achiev=
es both optimal convergence (~100% success like grid search) AND computatio=
nal efficiency (7-15=D7 faster), providing a "no-brainer" replacement for c=
urrent methods
=95 Validation Goal: Empirical benchmarking to demonstrate three metrics ac=
ross multiple datasets=97(1) accuracy: % finding true optimal, (2) precisio=
n: distance from optimal, (3) efficiency: compute time vs. baselines (Grid,=
 Random, Bayesian)
Here is the overview and related documents. I hope you do not mind AI outpu=
ts for some of the write up.


For Random Forest ML models, there are a certain number of "trees" that get=
 generated. In Python, this is traditionally or by default set to 100 trees=
. However, I had a question to my professor that I couldn't get answered - =
"why is the default 100", "is 100 the True optimal tree count", and "how ar=
e you able to determine what the 'optimal' tree count is"?

There are methods of converging in on the true optimal tree count, but they=
 are computationally prohibitive in certain scenarios. There are other meth=
ods that do not guarantee the optimal tree count but are a "good enough" ap=
proximation of true optimal (they are less precise but require less compute=
 so there is a cost benefit trade off).

The math should work out theoretically to show that the two-phase search is=
 both optimal, converges on a true optimal near 100% of the time similar to=
 grid search, but is computationally efficient (theoretically it is). Howev=
er, the point of the research and what we would be looking to publish is a =
table that shows 1) how often the search method finds the true optimal (acc=
uracy), 20 how close to optimal and the range spread around optimal it gets=
 (precision), and 3) how it compares in time  to generate the output compar=
ed to the other methods (compute time or compute efficiency).

We would hope that the new method is faster than grid search AND is more ac=
curate/precise than the Bayesian tuning. In that case, it becomes a no brai=
ner to use this method for hyper parameter tuning because anyone who has th=
e compute for grid search would likely choose this because it is still opti=
mal for less time AND it would enable people who do not have enough compute=
 for grid search to use this method as it would be less time or comparable =
time (hopefully) but yield a better recommended optimal than the other "goo=
d enough" search methods.

I am working on the code blocks and will get them over to you soon. Let me =
know if you have any questions or if there is a better way for me to explai=
n it. Project timeline is pretty fast after I get the code generated, but i=
t might take a few weekends with school and my time management.

Let me know if you want to talk through it more next week(end).

